Your investments will be made into the 'St. James's Place Personal Retirement Plan' scheme.

There is no limit to the amount you can contribute annually to your pension plan. However there will be a tax charge on contributions made by you, or on your behalf, which exceed an Annual Allowance set by HM Revenue & Customs. The Annual Allowance for 2019/2020 is £40,000.00. Tax relief will be granted on personal contributions up to 100% of earnings, or the Annual Allowance if less. If your contributions have been less than the Annual Allowance in the last three years, unused amounts may be used in this tax year. For individuals whose earnings are below £3,600.00 or are nil, relief will be given on contributions up to £3,600.00.

If you have taken an Uncrystallised Funds Pension Lump Sum payment, were in Flexible Drawdown pre 6 April 2015, or are in Flexi-Access Drawdown post 6 April 2015 and have taken any income, your Annual Allowance is restricted to £4,000.00 and you are unable to pay contributions in respect of unused relief from previous tax years.
You have chosen to invest in the Managed Funds Portfolio.
The following table shows the funds in which you have chosen to invest and the proportion of your investments in each fund.

1) The illustrated benefits in the table and graph are only examples and are not guaranteed,
they are not minimum or maximum amounts and you could get back less than you paid in. We will write to you each year to enable you to review your benefits.
2) Price inflation reduces the worth of all savings and investments. The illustrated value of your

benefits, that might be payable when you retire, has been shown in  today’s money . This allows for the effect of price rises and gives an indication of what the buying power of your benefits could be in the future. We have assumed that the rate of price inflation is 2.00% every year.
3) The Financial Conduct Authority sets maximum growth rates that can be used in projections.

These rates, after allowing for the effects of inflation, are -0.10%, 2.90%, and 5.90% each year. All firms use these except where they believe a lower rate will give a more realistic indication of potential future returns. We have used growth rate assumptions that are below the maximum for the following funds you have selected:
Lower Rate Mid Rate Higher Rate
The maximum growth rate assumptions have been used for the other funds you have
4) The annual income figures assume you buy a pension annuity that provides you with a
set monthly income, paid for at least 5 years.
5) We have assumed that the tax free cash sum available will be 25% of the uncrystallised fund
value, subject to a maximum of 25% of the standard Lifetime Allowance.
6) Your eventual benefits could be more or less than the illustrated figures in the tables. The
amount will depend on how your investments grow up to the time you buy an annuity, the tax treatment of your investments and the annuity rates available at that time.

How much will the advice cost?
How much will the advice cost?
The cost of the initial advice and our services will be £19,765

This is 2.25% of the investment shown. This cost covers all of our expenses incurred in providing, checking and guaranteeing the suitability of your advice. The remuneration of your Partner's practice is only one element of this cost, from which they meet their own business expenses.

We will also provide you with ongoing advice to review your investment and ensure it remains appropriate, as set out in the brochure  "Welcome to St. James's Place"  provided by your Partner. The cost of this each year is 0.50% of your total investment (and so this annual cost will increase if your investment grows).
For example, if your investments are worth £879,000 in a year, the cost for that year would be £4,395.
